<!--template match = subSubSection[ancestor::treatment]--><tp:treatment-sec sec-type="diagnosis">
<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
Differential diagnosis.
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>Macrosaldula graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

is similar to the group of east Palaearctic species with completely dark coloured hemelytra—the South Far Eastern 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. koreana</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. violacea</tp:taxon-name>
, the South Siberian 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. simulans</tp:taxon-name>
, and the Siberian-Nearctic 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. rivularia</tp:taxon-name>
. 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>Macrosaldula koreana</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. violacea</tp:taxon-name>
share the shiny dorsum with 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

, while 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. rivularia</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. simulans</tp:taxon-name>
have the dorsum matt. Externally, these four species differ by the very short dorsal setae (
<!--template match = figureCitation--><xref rid="fig-7--151-264-1832-1856-">Figs. 18–22</xref>
), while 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

has long erect setae on the dorsum.
</p>
<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
However, the resemblance to 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. koreana</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. rivularia</tp:taxon-name>
is only superficial, 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

does not belong to the ‘aberrant group of species 
sensu
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref7241">Cobben (1985)</xref>
’, having a different structure of the medial endosomal sclerite.
</p>
</tp:treatment-sec>
<!--template match = subSubSection[ancestor::treatment]--><tp:treatment-sec sec-type="discussion">
<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
Of the Central Asian species of the genus, 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

is similar to 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. tadzhika ( Kiritshenko, 1912 )</tp:taxon-name>
by the presence of long erect setae on the dorsum of the body, but the latter species differs in the smaller body size, the presence of light spots on the corium, and the structure of the male genitalia (see 
<!--template match = figureCitation--><xref rid="fig-">Figs. 34–47</xref>
). The extremely dark individuals of the Central Asian 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. jakowleffi</tp:taxon-name>
(
<!--template match = figureCitation--><xref rid="fig-7--151-264-1832-1856-">Fig. 22</xref>
) can be confused with 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>M. graziae</tp:taxon-name>

<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.

<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>Macrosaldula jakowleffi</tp:taxon-name>
has the same long erect setae on the head and pronotum, but differs from the new species by the following features: matt hemelytra with short erect setae on corium, processus hamatus of paramere attenuating evenly to the apex (
<!--template match = figureCitation--><xref rid="fig-5--151-264-1928-1952-">Fig. 7</xref>
), and pegs on male grasping plate dense (
<!--template match = figureCitation--><xref rid="fig-5--151-264-1928-1952-">Fig. 8</xref>
).
</p>
</tp:treatment-sec>
